@tideomega You can't do that, so don't even try.

You can convert and lower bitrates, that's fine, but if you get a crappy quality mp3 of 32kbps, you can't convert it up to 128kbps and expect it to sound good. Once the quality is ruined it cannot be restored.

And to answer your question, yes, the higher the bitrate, the better the sound within its respective compression type (i.e. CBR, VBR, ABR). Each have their advantages and disadvantages, but it basically works by removing the sound ranges usually inaudible to human hearing. Hence, if you lower too much, it removes ranges of sound that ARE audible. Basically 128kbps is a decent audio rate for most people is fine, but you can have it a bit higher if you are finicky and can notice the difference. 320kbps for example is overkill for most people and uses up a lot of space.
